Instance Block OR Non-static Block

    Let’s say you’re creating a class called com.Consturctor.Book. Every time you create a new com.Consturctor.Book object, you want to do some setup — maybe print a message
    and set a default value like edition = 1. You want this setup to happen every time you create a new book, no matter what data is assigned later.

    Now imagine having to repeat that same setup code again and again in different places. That would make your program longer, harder to manage,
    and easier to break if you forget something. Wouldn’t it be better if you could just write this setup code once — and have it run every time a new object is created?

    That’s exactly what instance blocks are for.

Q1. What Exactly is an Instance Block?
    Instance blocks in Java, often called initializer blocks, are blocks of code that are executed every time a new instance of a class is created.
    They are useful for initializing common parts across different parts of a class or when anonymous classes are involved.

Standard Definition:
    An instance block in Java is a block of code inside a class that runs automatically every time a new object is created.

# Real-Life Analogy to Understand Better:

    Imagine a book printing machine in a factory. Every time a new book is printed, the machine automatically adds a barcode and the publisher’s logo on the last page.
    This setup happens for every book, no matter what the book’s title or author is.

    The machine doesn’t care about what content is inside — it just runs this default action every time a book is created.

    In Java, the instance block behaves the same way. It runs automatically for every new object, performing a shared setup like assigning default values
    or printing setup messages. You don’t have to call it — it just runs, behind the scenes.

# Key Takeaways
    1. Instance blocks in Java are also called initializer blocks
    2. They run every time a new object is created
    3. They run before any other object setup happens
    4. You can use them to set default values or run object-level setup logic
    5. You don’t need to call them — Java runs them automatically
    6. Instance blocks can access instance variables
    7. They help keep your code cleaner and less repetitive

# Common Interview Questions:

    Q1. What is an instance block in Java?
        An instance block is a block of code that runs automatically every time a new object is created. It helps set default values or perform setup tasks.

    Q2. How is an instance block different from a static block?
        A static block runs once when the class is loaded. An instance block runs every time an object is created.

    Q3. Can we have more than one instance block in a class?
        Yes, you can have multiple instance blocks, and Java will run them in the order they appear in the code.

    Q4. Can instance blocks access instance variables?
        Yes. Instance blocks run in the context of the object, so they can use instance variables and call instance methods.

    Q5. Where are instance blocks useful?
        Instance blocks are useful when you want to avoid repeating setup code across multiple places or when using anonymous classes where constructors aren’t available.

    Q6. What is the order of execution when we use static blocks, instance blocks?
        First, all static blocks (once). Then, each time an object is created: all instance blocks (in order).

Summary:
    1. Static blocks run once, when the class is loaded.
    2. Instance blocks run every time a new object is created.
    3. You can have multiple static and instance blocks in one class.
    4. Java runs them in the order they appear in the code.
    5. This gives you better control over setup logic, whether it's for the class or for each object.
    6. Helps keep your code organized and clean, especially when you need to perform different tasks during setup.